Loading the files from the zip

options(timeout = 6000)
download.file("https://ethz-ins.org/content/w10.assignment.zip", "w10.practical.zip")
unzip("w10.practical.zip")
list.files()
## [1] "assignment.html"   "assignment.Rmd"    "Creb1.bed"        
## [4] "Creb1.bw"          "Creb3.bed"         "Creb3.bw"         
## [7] "Creb3L1.bed"       "Creb3L1.bw"        "w10.practical.zip"
# importing the two files 
tracks <- list.files(pattern="bw$")

regions <- list.files(pattern="bed$")


# we first import the peaks
peaks <- lapply(regions, rtracklayer::import.bed)
# we'll focus on the high-quality peaks
peaks <- lapply(peaks, FUN=function(x) x[x$score>800])
# we get the union of non-redundant regions
regions <- reduce(unlist(GRangesList(peaks)))


#plotting the signal to matrix 
ml <- signal2Matrix(tracks, regions, extend=2000)
## Reading Creb1.bw
## Reading Creb3.bw
## Reading Creb3L1.bw
set.seed(123)  # to ensure that it gives the same results everytime
nf <- getNormFactors(tracks, useSeqLevels="chr1")
## Comparing coverage in random regions...
ml <- rescaleSignalMatrices(ml, scaleFactors=nf)

plotEnrichedHeatmaps(ml)

Clustering

set.seed(123)

cl2 <- clusterSignalMatrices(ml, k=2:10) # plotting the clusters from 2 to 10, here can see on the graph the ideal number 
ggplot(cl2$varExplained, aes(k, varExplained)) + geom_line()

cl <- clusterSignalMatrices(ml, k=6)
##   ~76% of the variance explained by clusters
mycolors <- c("1"="red", "2"="blue", "3"="darkgreen", "4"="black","5"="orange", "6"="pink")
plotEnrichedHeatmaps(ml, row_split=cl, mean_color=mycolors)

breakStrings <- function(x, minSizeForBreak=20, lb="\n"){
   sapply(x,minSizeForBreak=minSizeForBreak,lb=lb,FUN=function(x,minSizeForBreak,lb){
      if(nchar(x)<=minSizeForBreak) return(x)
      g <- gregexpr(" ", x)[[1]]
      if(length(g)==0) return(x)
      if(length(g)==1 & all(g==-1)) return(x)
      mid <- nchar(x)/2
      mid <- g[order(abs(g-mid))[1]]
      substr(x, mid, mid) <- lb
      return(x)
   })
}
ggplot(head(bp,15), aes(Hyper_Fold_Enrichment, reorder(breakStrings(name), Hyper_Adjp_BH), size=Hyper_Foreground_Region_Hits, color=-log10(Hyper_Adjp_BH))) + geom_point() + scale_color_viridis_c()

The genes, which CREB is regulating, are associated with various factors. Most importantly in this sample there is a significant up-regulation of the genes associated with signal transduction, response to chemicals and response to stimuli (most significant). However these genes have a low hyper fold enrichment, compared to genes associated with regulation of mononuclear cell proliferation, regulation of leukocyte proliferation and regulation of receptor activity. Concluding the most active regions are genes associated especially with the response to stimuli, followed by signal transduction. The response stimuli makes sense, as CREB is associated with the mechanisms involved with the response to stimulus.
